# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pcr-amplification
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] A **DNA polymerase** is a member of a family of enzymes that catalyze the synthesis of DNA molecules from nucleoside triphosphates, the molecular precursors of DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] These enzymes are essential for DNA replication and usually work in groups to create two identical DNA duplexes from a single original DNA duplex.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] During this process, DNA polymerase "reads" the existing DNA strands to create two new strands that match the existing ones.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] DNA polymerase adds nucleotides to the three prime (3')-end of a DNA strand, one nucleotide at a time.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Every time a cell divides, DNA polymerases are required to duplicate the cell's DNA, so that a copy of the original DNA molecule can be passed to each daughter cell.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] In this way, genetic information is passed down from generation to generation.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Before replication can take place, an enzyme called helicase unwinds the DNA molecule from its tightly woven form, in the process breaking the hydrogen bonds between the nucleotide bases.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] This opens up or "unzips" the double-stranded DNA to give two single strands of DNA that can be used as templates for replication in the above reaction.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] In 1956, Arthur Kornberg and colleagues discovered DNA polymerase I (Pol I), in *Escherichia coli*.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] They described the DNA replication process by which DNA polymerase copies the base sequence of a template DNA strand.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Kornberg was later awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1959 for this work.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] DNA polymerase II was discovered by Thomas Kornberg (the son of Arthur Kornberg) and Malcolm E.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Gefter in 1970 while further elucidating the role of Pol I in *E. coli* DNA replication.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Three more DNA polymerases have been found in *E. coli*, including DNA polymerase III (discovered in the 1970s) and DNA polymerases IV and V (discovered in 1999).
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] From 1983 on, DNA polymerases have been used in the polymerase chain reaction (PCR), and from 1988 thermostable DNA polymerases were used instead, as they do not need to be added in every cycle of a PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The main function of DNA polymerase is to synthesize DNA from deoxyribonucleotides, the building blocks of DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The DNA copies are created by the pairing of nucleotides to bases present on each strand of the original DNA molecule.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] This pairing always occurs in specific combinations, with cytosine along with guanine, and thymine along with adenine, forming two separate pairs, respectively.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] By contrast, RNA polymerases synthesize RNA from ribonucleotides from either RNA or DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] When synthesizing new DNA, DNA polymerase can add free nucleotides only to the 3' end of the newly forming strand.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] This results in elongation of the newly forming strand in a 5'–3' direction.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The directionality of the newly forming strand (the daughter strand) is opposite to the direction in which DNA polymerase moves along the template strand.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Since DNA polymerase requires a free 3' OH group for initiation of synthesis, it can synthesize in only one direction by extending the 3' end of the preexisting nucleotide chain.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Hence, DNA polymerase moves along the template strand in a 3'–5' direction, and the daughter strand is formed in a 5'–3' direction.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] This difference enables the resultant double-strand DNA formed to be composed of two DNA strands that are antiparallel to each other.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The function of DNA polymerase is not quite perfect, with the enzyme making about one mistake for every billion base pairs copied.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Error correction is a property of some, but not all DNA polymerases.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] This process corrects mistakes in newly synthesized DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] When an incorrect base pair is recognized, DNA polymerase moves backwards by one base pair of DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The 3'–5' exonuclease activity of the enzyme allows the incorrect base pair to be excised (this activity is known as *proofreading*).
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Following base excision, the polymerase can re-insert the correct base and replication can continue forwards.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] This preserves the integrity of the original DNA strand that is passed onto the daughter cells.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Fidelity is very important in DNA replication.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Mismatches in DNA base pairing can potentially result in dysfunctional proteins and could lead to cancer.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Many DNA polymerases contain an exonuclease domain, which acts in detecting base pair mismatches and further performs in the removal of the incorrect nucleotide to be replaced by the correct one.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The shape and the interactions accommodating the Watson and Crick base pair are what primarily contribute to the detection or error.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Hydrogen bonds play a key role in base pair binding and interaction.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The loss of an interaction, which occurs at a mismatch, is said to trigger a shift in the balance, for the binding of the template-primer, from the polymerase, to the exonuclease domain.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] In addition, an incorporation of a wrong nucleotide causes a retard in DNA polymerization.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] This delay gives time for the DNA to be switched from the polymerase site to the exonuclease site.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Different conformational changes and loss of interaction occur at different mismatches.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] In a purine:pyrimidine mismatch there is a displacement of the pyrimidine towards the major groove and the purine towards the minor groove.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Relative to the shape of DNA polymerase's binding pocket, steric clashes occur between the purine and residues in the minor groove, and important van der Waals and electrostatic interactions are lost by the pyrimidine.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pyrimidine:pyrimidine and purine:purine mismatches present less notable changes since the bases are displaced towards the major groove, and less steric hindrance is experienced.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] However, although the different mismatches result in different steric properties, DNA polymerase is still able to detect and differentiate them so uniformly and maintain fidelity in DNA replication.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] DNA polymerization is also critical for many mutagenesis processes and is widely employed in biotechnologies.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The known DNA polymerases have highly conserved structure, which means that their overall catalytic subunits vary very little from species to species, independent of their domain structures.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Conserved structures usually indicate important, irreplaceable functions of the cell, the maintenance of which provides evolutionary advantages.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The shape can be described as resembling a right hand with thumb, finger, and palm domains.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The palm domain appears to function in catalyzing the transfer of phosphoryl groups in the phosphoryl transfer reaction.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] DNA is bound to the palm when the enzyme is active.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] This reaction is believed to be catalyzed by a two-metal-ion mechanism.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The finger domain functions to bind the nucleoside triphosphates with the template base.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The thumb domain plays a potential role in the processivity, translocation, and positioning of the DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] DNA polymerase's rapid catalysis is due to its processive nature.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Processivity is a characteristic of enzymes that function on polymeric substrates.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] In the case of DNA polymerase, the degree of processivity refers to the average number of nucleotides added each time the enzyme binds a template.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The average DNA polymerase requires about one second locating and binding a primer/template junction.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Once it is bound, a nonprocessive DNA polymerase adds nucleotides at a rate of one nucleotide per second.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Processive DNA polymerases, however, add multiple nucleotides per second, drastically increasing the rate of DNA synthesis.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The degree of processivity is directly proportional to the rate of DNA synthesis.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The rate of DNA synthesis in a living cell was first determined as the rate of phage T4 DNA elongation in phage infected *E. coli*.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] During the period of exponential DNA increase at 37 °C, the rate was 749 nucleotides per second.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] DNA polymerase's ability to slide along the DNA template allows increased processivity.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] There is a dramatic increase in processivity at the replication fork.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] This increase is facilitated by the DNA polymerase's association with proteins known as the sliding DNA clamp.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The clamps are multiple protein subunits associated in the shape of a ring.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Using the hydrolysis of ATP, a class of proteins known as the sliding clamp loading proteins open up the ring structure of the sliding DNA clamps allowing binding to and release from the DNA strand.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Protein–protein interaction with the clamp prevents DNA polymerase from diffusing from the DNA template, thereby ensuring that the enzyme binds the same primer/template junction and continues replication.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] DNA polymerase changes conformation, increasing affinity to the clamp when associated with it and decreasing affinity when it completes the replication of a stretch of DNA to allow release from the clamp.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] DNA polymerase processivity has been studied with in vitro single-molecule experiments (namely, optical tweezers and magnetic tweezers) have revealed the synergies between DNA polymerases and other molecules of the replisome (helicases and SSBs) and with the DNA replication fork.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] These results have led to the development of synergetic kinetic models for DNA replication describing the resulting DNA polymerase processivity increase.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Based on sequence homology, DNA polymerases can be further subdivided into seven different families: A, B, C, D, X, Y, and RT.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Some viruses also encode special DNA polymerases, such as Hepatitis B virus DNA polymerase.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] These may selectively replicate viral DNA through a variety of mechanisms.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Retroviruses encode an unusual DNA polymerase called reverse transcriptase, which is an RNA-dependent DNA polymerase (RdDp).
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] It polymerizes DNA from a template of RNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Prokaryotic polymerases exist in two forms: core polymerase and holoenzyme.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Core polymerase synthesizes DNA from the DNA template but it cannot initiate the synthesis alone or accurately.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Holoenzyme accurately initiates synthesis.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Prokaryotic family A polymerases include the DNA polymerase I (Pol I) enzyme, which is encoded by the *polA* gene and ubiquitous among prokaryotes.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] This repair polymerase is involved in excision repair with both 3'–5' and 5'–3' exonuclease activity and processing of Okazaki fragments generated during lagging strand synthesis.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol I is the most abundant polymerase, accounting for >95% of polymerase activity in *E. coli*; yet cells lacking Pol I have been found suggesting Pol I activity can be replaced by the other four polymerases.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol I adds ~15-20 nucleotides per second, thus showing poor processivity.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Instead, Pol I starts adding nucleotides at the RNA primer:template junction known as the origin of replication (ori).
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Approximately 400 bp downstream from the origin, the Pol III holoenzyme is assembled and takes over replication at a highly processive speed and nature.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] DNA polymerase II is a family B polymerase encoded by the polB gene.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol II has 3'–5' exonuclease activity and participates in DNA repair, replication restart to bypass lesions, and its cell presence can jump from ~30-50 copies per cell to ~200–300 during SOS induction.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol II is also thought to be a backup to Pol III as it can interact with holoenzyme proteins and assume a high level of processivity.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The main role of Pol II is thought to be the ability to direct polymerase activity at the replication fork and help stalled Pol III bypass terminal mismatches.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] DNA polymerase III holoenzyme is the primary enzyme involved in DNA replication in *E. coli* and belongs to family C polymerases.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] It consists of three assemblies: the pol III core, the beta sliding clamp processivity factor, and the clamp-loading complex.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The core consists of three subunits: α, the polymerase activity hub, ɛ, exonucleolytic proofreader, and θ, which may act as a stabilizer for ɛ.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The beta sliding clamp processivity factor is also present in duplicate, one for each core, to create a clamp that encloses DNA allowing for high processivity.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The third assembly is a seven-subunit (τ2γδδ′χψ) clamp loader complex.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The old textbook "trombone model" depicts an elongation complex with two equivalents of the core enzyme at each replication fork (RF), one for each strand, the lagging and leading.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] However, recent evidence from single-molecule studies indicates an average of three stoichiometric equivalents of core enzyme at each RF for both Pol III and its counterpart in *B. subtilis,* PolC.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] In-cell fluorescent microscopy has revealed that leading strand synthesis may not be completely continuous, and Pol III* (i.e., the holoenzyme α, ε, τ, δ and χ subunits without the ß2 sliding clamp) has a high frequency of dissociation from active RFs.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] In these studies, the replication fork turnover rate was about 10s for Pol III*, 47s for the ß2 sliding clamp, and 15m for the DnaB helicase.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] This suggests that the DnaB helicase may remain stably associated at RFs and serve as a nucleation point for the competent holoenzyme.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] *In vitro* single-molecule studies have shown that Pol III* has a high rate of RF turnover when in excess, but remains stably associated with replication forks when concentration is limiting.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Another single-molecule study showed that DnaB helicase activity and strand elongation can proceed with decoupled, stochastic kinetics.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] In *E. coli*, DNA polymerase IV (Pol IV) is an error-prone DNA polymerase involved in non-targeted mutagenesis.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol IV is a Family Y polymerase expressed by the *dinB* gene that is switched on via SOS induction caused by stalled polymerases at the replication fork.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] During SOS induction, Pol IV production is increased tenfold and one of the functions during this time is to interfere with Pol III holoenzyme processivity.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] This creates a checkpoint, stops replication, and allows time to repair DNA lesions via the appropriate repair pathway.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Another function of Pol IV is to perform translesion synthesis at the stalled replication fork like, for example, bypassing N2-deoxyguanine adducts at a faster rate than transversing undamaged DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Cells lacking the *dinB* gene have a higher rate of mutagenesis caused by DNA damaging agents.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] DNA polymerase V (Pol V) is a Y-family DNA polymerase that is involved in SOS response and translesion synthesis DNA repair mechanisms.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Transcription of Pol V via the *umuDC* genes is highly regulated to produce only Pol V when damaged DNA is present in the cell generating an SOS response.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Stalled polymerases causes RecA to bind to the ssDNA, which causes the LexA protein to autodigest.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] LexA then loses its ability to repress the transcription of the umuDC operon.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The same RecA-ssDNA nucleoprotein posttranslationally modifies the UmuD protein into UmuD' protein.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] UmuD and UmuD' form a heterodimer that interacts with UmuC, which in turn activates umuC's polymerase catalytic activity on damaged DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] In *E. coli*, a polymerase "tool belt" model for switching pol III with pol IV at a stalled replication fork, where both polymerases bind simultaneously to the β-clamp, has been proposed.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] However, the involvement of more than one TLS polymerase working in succession to bypass a lesion has not yet been shown in *E. coli*.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Moreover, Pol IV can catalyze both insertion and extension with high efficiency, whereas pol V is considered the major SOS TLS polymerase.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] One example is the bypass of intra strand guanine thymine cross-link where it was shown on the basis of the difference in the mutational signatures of the two polymerases, that pol IV and pol V compete for TLS of the intra-strand crosslink.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] In 1998, the family D of DNA polymerase was discovered in *Pyrococcus furiosus* and *Methanococcus jannaschii*.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The PolD complex is a heterodimer of two chains, each encoded by DP1 (small proofreading) and DP2 (large catalytic).
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Unlike other DNA polymerases, the structure and mechanism of the DP2 catalytic core resemble that of multi-subunit RNA polymerases.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The DP1-DP2 interface resembles that of Eukaryotic Class B polymerase zinc finger and its small subunit.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] DP1, a Mre11-like exonuclease, is likely the precursor of small subunit of Pol α and ε, providing proofreading capabilities now lost in Eukaryotes.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Its N-terminal HSH domain is similar to AAA proteins, especially Pol III subunit δ and RuvB, in structure.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] *Pyrococcus abyssi* polD is more heat-stable and more accurate than *Taq* polymerase, but has not yet been commercialized.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] It has been proposed that family D DNA polymerase was the first to evolve in cellular organisms and that the replicative polymerase of the Last Universal Cellular Ancestor (LUCA) belonged to family D.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Family X polymerases contain the well-known eukaryotic polymerase pol β (beta), as well as other eukaryotic polymerases such as Pol σ (sigma), Pol λ (lambda), Pol μ (mu), and Terminal deoxynucleotidyl transferase (TdT).
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Family X polymerases are found mainly in vertebrates, and a few are found in plants and fungi.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] These polymerases have highly conserved regions that include two helix-hairpin-helix motifs that are imperative in the DNA-polymerase interactions.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] One motif is located in the 8 kDa domain that interacts with downstream DNA and one motif is located in the thumb domain that interacts with the primer strand.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol β, encoded by POLB gene, is required for short-patch base excision repair, a DNA repair pathway that is essential for repairing alkylated or oxidized bases as well as abasic sites.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol λ and Pol μ, encoded by the POLL and POLM genes respectively, are involved in non-homologous end-joining, a mechanism for rejoining DNA double-strand breaks due to hydrogen peroxide and ionizing radiation, respectively.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] TdT is expressed only in lymphoid tissue, and adds "n nucleotides" to double-strand breaks formed during V(D)J recombination to promote immunological diversity.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol α (alpha), Pol δ (delta), and Pol ε (epsilon) are members of Family B Polymerases and are the main polymerases involved with nuclear DNA replication.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol α complex (pol α-DNA primase complex) consists of four subunits: the catalytic subunit POLA1, the regulatory subunit POLA2, and the small and the large primase subunits PRIM1 and PRIM2 respectively.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Once primase has created the RNA primer, Pol α starts replication elongating the primer with ~20 nucleotides.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Due to its high processivity, Pol δ takes over the leading and lagging strand synthesis from Pol α.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol δ is expressed by genes POLD1, creating the catalytic subunit, POLD2, POLD3, and POLD4 creating the other subunits that interact with Proliferating Cell Nuclear Antigen (PCNA), which is a DNA clamp that allows Pol δ to possess processivity.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol ε is encoded by the POLE1, the catalytic subunit, POLE2, and POLE3 gene.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] It has been reported that the function of Pol ε is to extend the leading strand during replication, while Pol δ primarily replicates the lagging strand; however, recent evidence suggested that Pol δ might have a role in replicating the leading strand of DNA as well.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol ε's C-terminus "polymerase relic" region, despite being unnecessary for polymerase activity, is thought to be essential to cell vitality.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The C-terminus region is thought to provide a checkpoint before entering anaphase, provide stability to the holoenzyme, and add proteins to the holoenzyme necessary for initiation of replication.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol ε has a larger "palm" domain that provides high processivity independently of PCNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Compared to other Family B polymerases, the DEDD exonuclease family responsible for proofreading is inactivated in Pol α.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol ε is unique in that it has two zinc finger domains and an inactive copy of another family B polymerase in its C-terminal.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The presence of this zinc finger has implications in the origins of Eukaryota, which in this case is placed into the *Asgard* group with archaeal B3 polymerase.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol η (eta), Pol ι (iota), and Pol κ (kappa), are Family Y DNA polymerases involved in the DNA repair by translation synthesis and encoded by genes POLH, POLI, and POLK respectively.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Members of Family Y have five common motifs to aid in binding the substrate and primer terminus and they all include the typical right hand thumb, palm and finger domains with added domains like little finger (LF), polymerase-associated domain (PAD), or wrist.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The active site, however, differs between family members due to the different lesions being repaired.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Polymerases in Family Y are low-fidelity polymerases, but have been proven to do more good than harm as mutations that affect the polymerase can cause various diseases, such as skin cancer and Xeroderma Pigmentosum Variant (XPS).
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The importance of these polymerases is evidenced by the fact that gene encoding DNA polymerase η is referred as XPV, because loss of this gene results in the disease Xeroderma Pigmentosum Variant.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol η is particularly important for allowing accurate translesion synthesis of DNA damage resulting from ultraviolet radiation.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The functionality of Pol κ is not completely understood, but researchers have found two probable functions.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol κ is thought to act as an extender or an inserter of a specific base at certain DNA lesions.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] All three translesion synthesis polymerases, along with Rev1, are recruited to damaged lesions via stalled replicative DNA polymerases.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] There are two pathways of damage repair leading researchers to conclude that the chosen pathway depends on which strand contains the damage, the leading or lagging strand.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol ζ, another B family polymerase, is made of two subunits: Rev3 – the catalytic subunit; and Rev7 (MAD2L2) – which increases the catalytic function of the polymerase, and is involved in translation synthesis.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol ζ lacks 3' to 5' exonuclease activity, and is unique in that it can extend primers with terminal mismatches.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Rev1 has three regions of interest in the BRCT domain, ubiquitin-binding domain, and C-terminal domain and has dCMP transferase ability, which adds deoxycytidine opposite lesions that would stall replicative polymerases Pol δ and Pol ε.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] These stalled polymerases activate ubiquitin complexes that, in turn, disassociate replication polymerases and recruit Pol ζ and Rev1.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Together, Pol ζ and Rev1 add deoxycytidine, and Pol ζ extends past the lesion.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Through a yet undetermined process, Pol ζ disassociates, and replication polymerases reassociate and continue replication.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol ζ and Rev1 are not required for replication, but loss of REV3 gene in budding yeast can cause increased sensitivity to DNA-damaging agents due to collapse of replication forks where replication polymerases have stalled.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Telomerase is a ribonucleoprotein which functions to replicate ends of linear chromosomes since normal DNA polymerase cannot replicate the ends, or telomeres.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The single-strand 3' overhang of the double-strand chromosome with the sequence 5'-TTAGGG-3' recruits telomerase.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Telomerase acts like other DNA polymerases by extending the 3' end, but, unlike other DNA polymerases, telomerase does not require a template.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The TERT subunit, an example of a reverse transcriptase, uses the RNA subunit to form the primer–template junction that allows telomerase to extend the 3' end of chromosome ends.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The gradual decrease in size of telomeres as the result of many replications over a lifetime are thought to be associated with the effects of aging.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol γ (gamma), Pol θ (theta), and Pol ν (nu) are Family A polymerases.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol γ, encoded by the POLG gene, was long thought to be the only mitochondrial polymerase.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] However, recent research shows that at least Pol β (beta), a Family X polymerase, is also present in mitochondria.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Any mutation that leads to limited or non-functioning Pol γ has a significant effect on mtDNA and is the most common cause of autosomal inherited mitochondrial disorders.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol γ contains a C-terminus polymerase domain and an N-terminus 3'–5' exonuclease domain that are connected via the linker region, which binds the accessory subunit.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The accessory subunit binds DNA and is required for processivity of Pol γ.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Point mutation A467T in the linker region is responsible for more than one-third of all Pol γ-associated mitochondrial disorders.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] While many homologs of Pol θ, encoded by the POLQ gene, are found in eukaryotes, its function is not clearly understood.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The sequence of amino acids in the C-terminus is what classifies Pol θ as Family A polymerase, although the error rate for Pol θ is more closely related to Family Y polymerases.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol θ extends mismatched primer termini and can bypass abasic sites by adding a nucleotide.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] It also has Deoxyribophosphodiesterase (dRPase) activity in the polymerase domain and can show ATPase activity in close proximity to ssDNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Pol ν (nu) is considered to be the least effective of the polymerase enzymes.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] However, DNA polymerase nu plays an active role in homology repair during cellular responses to crosslinks, fulfilling its role in a complex with helicase.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Plants use two Family A polymerases to copy both the mitochondrial and plastid genomes.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] They are more similar to bacterial Pol I than they are to mammalian Pol γ.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Retroviruses encode an unusual DNA polymerase called reverse transcriptase, which is an RNA-dependent DNA polymerase (RdDp) that synthesizes DNA from a template of RNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The reverse transcriptase family contain both DNA polymerase functionality and RNase H functionality, which degrades RNA base-paired to DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Reverse transcriptase is commonly employed in amplification of RNA for research purposes.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Using an RNA template, PCR can utilize reverse transcriptase, creating a DNA template.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] This new DNA template can then be used for typical PCR amplification.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The products of such an experiment are thus amplified PCR products from RNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Each HIV retrovirus particle contains two RNA genomes, but, after an infection, each virus generates only one provirus.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] After infection, reverse transcription is accompanied by template switching between the two genome copies (copy choice recombination).
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] From 5 to 14 recombination events per genome occur at each replication cycle.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Template switching (recombination) appears to be necessary for maintaining genome integrity and as a repair mechanism for salvaging damaged genomes.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] Bacteriophage (phage) T4 encodes a DNA polymerase that catalyzes DNA synthesis in a 5' to 3' direction.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] The phage polymerase also has an exonuclease activity that acts in a 3' to 5' direction, and this activity is employed in the proofreading and editing of newly inserted bases.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] A phage mutant with a temperature sensitive DNA polymerase, when grown at permissive temperatures, was observed to undergo recombination at frequencies that are about two-fold higher than that of wild-type phage.
[src:pcr-amplification/dna-polymerase] It was proposed that a mutational alteration in the phage DNA polymerase can stimulate template strand switching (copy choice recombination) during replication.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The **polymerase chain reaction** (**PCR**) is a laboratory method widely used to amplify copies of specific DNA sequences rapidly, to enable detailed study.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] PCR was invented in 1983 by American biochemist Kary Mullis at Cetus Corporation.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Mullis and biochemist Michael Smith, who had developed other essential ways of manipulating DNA, were jointly awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1993.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] PCR is fundamental to many of the procedures used in genetic testing, research, including analysis of ancient samples of DNA, and identification of infectious agents.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Using PCR, copies of very small amounts of DNA sequences are exponentially amplified in a series of cycles of temperature changes.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] PCR is now a common and often indispensable technique used in medical laboratory research for a broad variety of applications including biomedical research and forensic science.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The majority of PCR methods rely on thermal cycling.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Thermal cycling exposes reagents to repeated cycles of heating and cooling to permit different temperature-dependent reactions—specifically, DNA melting and enzyme-driven DNA replication.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] PCR employs two main reagents—primers (which are short single strand DNA fragments known as oligonucleotides that are a complementary sequence to the target DNA region) and a thermostable DNA polymerase.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] In the first step of PCR, the two strands of the DNA double helix are physically separated at a high temperature in a process called nucleic acid denaturation.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] In the second step, the temperature is lowered and the primers bind to the complementary sequences of DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The two DNA strands then become templates for DNA polymerase to enzymatically assemble a new DNA strand from free nucleotides, the building blocks of DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] As PCR progresses, the DNA generated is itself used as a template for replication, setting in motion a chain reaction in which the original DNA template is exponentially amplified.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Almost all PCR applications employ a heat-stable DNA polymerase, such as *Taq* polymerase, an enzyme originally isolated from the thermophilic bacterium *Thermus aquaticus*.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] If the polymerase used was heat-susceptible, it would denature under the high temperatures of the denaturation step.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Before the use of *Taq* polymerase, DNA polymerase had to be manually added every cycle, which was a tedious and costly process.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] PCR amplifies a specific region of a DNA strand (the DNA target).
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Most PCR methods amplify DNA fragments of between 0.1 and 10 kilo-base pairs (kbp) in length, although some techniques allow for amplification of fragments up to 40 kbp.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The amount of amplified product is determined by the available substrates in the reaction, which becomes limiting as the reaction progresses.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The reaction is commonly carried out in a volume of 10–200 μL in small reaction tubes (0.2–0.5 mL volumes) in a thermal cycler.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The thermal cycler heats and cools the reaction tubes to achieve the temperatures required at each step of the reaction (see below).
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Many modern thermal cyclers make use of a Peltier device, which permits both heating and cooling of the block holding the PCR tubes simply by reversing the device's electric current.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Thin-walled reaction tubes permit favorable thermal conductivity to allow for rapid thermal equilibrium.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Most thermal cyclers have heated lids to prevent condensation at the top of the reaction tube.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Older thermal cyclers lacking a heated lid require a layer of oil on top of the reaction mixture or a ball of wax inside the tube.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Typically, PCR consists of a series of 20–40 repeated temperature changes, called thermal cycles, with each cycle commonly consisting of two or three discrete temperature steps (see figure below).
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The cycling is often preceded by a single temperature step at a very high temperature (>90 °C (194 °F)), and followed by one hold at the end for final product extension or brief storage.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The temperatures used and the length of time they are applied in each cycle depend on a variety of parameters, including the enzyme used for DNA synthesis, the concentration of bivalent ions and dNTPs in the reaction, and the melting temperature (*Tm*) of the primers.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The individual steps common to most PCR methods are : initialization, annealing and extension.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] It is critical to determine a proper temperature for the annealing step because efficiency and specificity are strongly affected by the annealing temperature.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] to a perfectly complementary part of the strand, and nowhere else.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] If the temperature is too low, the primer may bind imperfectly.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] If it is too high, the primer may not bind at all.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Stable hydrogen bonds between complementary bases are formed only when the primer sequence very closely matches the template sequence.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] During this step, the polymerase binds to the primer-template hybrid and begins DNA formation.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The processes of denaturation, annealing and elongation constitute a single cycle.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Multiple cycles are required to amplify the DNA target to millions of copies.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] , or 1,073,741,824 copies of the original double-stranded DNA target region.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] To check whether the PCR successfully generated the anticipated DNA target region (also sometimes referred to as the amplimer or amplicon), agarose gel electrophoresis may be employed for size separation of the PCR products.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The size of the PCR products is determined by comparison with a DNA ladder, a molecular weight marker which contains DNA fragments of known sizes, which runs on the gel alongside the PCR products.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] As with other chemical reactions, the reaction rate and efficiency of PCR are affected by limiting factors.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] In practice, PCR can fail for various reasons, such as sensitivity or contamination.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] **Contamination** with extraneous DNA can lead to spurious products and is addressed with lab protocols and procedures that separate pre-PCR mixtures from potential DNA contaminants.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] For instance, if DNA from a crime scene is analyzed, a single DNA molecule from lab personnel could be amplified and misguide the investigation.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Hence the PCR-setup areas is separated from the analysis or purification of other PCR products, disposable plasticware used, and the work surface between reaction setups needs to be thoroughly cleaned.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] PCR allows isolation of DNA fragments from genomic DNA by selective amplification of a specific region of DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] This use of PCR augments, such as generating hybridization probes for Southern or northern hybridization and DNA cloning, which require larger amounts of DNA, representing a specific DNA region.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] PCR supplies these techniques with high amounts of pure DNA, enabling analysis of DNA samples even from very small amounts of starting material.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Bacterial colonies *(such as E. coli)* can be rapidly screened by PCR for correct DNA vector constructs.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] PCR may also be used for genetic fingerprinting; a forensic technique used to identify a person or organism by comparing experimental DNAs through different PCR-based methods.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Some PCR fingerprint methods have high discriminative power and can be used to identify genetic relationships between individuals, such as parent-child or between siblings, and are used in paternity testing (Fig.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] This technique may also be used to determine evolutionary relationships among organisms when certain molecular clocks are used (i.e. the 16S rRNA and recA genes of microorganisms).
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Because PCR amplifies the regions of DNA that it targets, PCR can be used to analyze extremely small amounts of sample.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] This is often critical for forensic analysis, when only a trace amount of DNA is available as evidence.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] PCR may also be used in the analysis of ancient DNA that is tens of thousands of years old.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] These PCR-based techniques have been successfully used on animals, such as a forty-thousand-year-old mammoth, and also on human DNA, in applications ranging from the analysis of Egyptian mummies to the identification of a Russian tsar and the body of English king Richard III.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Quantitative PCR or Real Time PCR, (qPCR not to be confused with RT-PCR) methods allow the estimation of the amount of a given sequence present in a sample—a technique often applied to quantitatively determine levels of gene expression.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The MIQE guidelines written by professors Stephen Bustin, Michael Pfaffl, Mikael Kubista and colleagues outline how qPCR experiments shall be performed and the results reported.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Quantitative PCR is an established tool for DNA quantification that measures the accumulation of DNA product after each round of PCR amplification.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] qPCR allows the quantification and detection of a specific DNA sequence in real time since it measures concentration while the synthesis process is taking place.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] There are two methods for simultaneous detection and quantification.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The first method consists of using fluorescent dyes that are retained nonspecifically in between the double strands.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The second method involves probes that code for specific sequences and are fluorescently labeled.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Detection of DNA using these methods can only be seen after the hybridization of probes with its complementary DNA (cDNA) takes place.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] An interesting technique combination is real-time PCR and reverse transcription.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] This sophisticated technique, called RT-qPCR, allows for the quantification of a small quantity of RNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Through this combined technique, mRNA is converted to cDNA, which is further quantified using qPCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] This technique lowers the possibility of error at the end point of PCR, increasing chances for detection of genes associated with genetic diseases such as cancer.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Laboratories use RT-qPCR for the purpose of sensitively measuring gene regulation.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The mathematical foundations for the reliable quantification of the PCR and RT-qPCR facilitate the implementation of accurate fitting procedures of experimental data in research, medical, diagnostic and infectious disease applications.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Prospective parents can be tested for being genetic carriers, or their children might be tested for actually being affected by a disease.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] DNA samples for prenatal testing can be obtained by amniocentesis, chorionic villus sampling, or even by the analysis of rare fetal cells circulating in the mother's bloodstream.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] PCR analysis is also essential to preimplantation genetic diagnosis, where individual cells of a developing embryo are tested for mutations.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] PCR allows for rapid and highly specific diagnosis of infectious diseases, including those caused by bacteria or viruses.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] PCR also permits identification of non-cultivatable or slow-growing microorganisms such as mycobacteria, anaerobic bacteria, or viruses from tissue culture assays and animal models.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The basis for PCR diagnostic applications in microbiology is the detection of infectious agents and the discrimination of non-pathogenic from pathogenic strains by virtue of specific genes.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] It is fairly simple to understand and to use, and produces results rapidly.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The technique is highly sensitive with the potential to produce millions to billions of copies of a specific product for sequencing, cloning, and analysis. qRT-PCR shares the same advantages as the PCR, with an added advantage of quantification of the synthesized product.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Therefore, it has its uses to analyze alterations of gene expression levels in tumors, microbes, or other disease states.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] PCR is a very powerful and practical research tool.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The sequencing of unknown etiologies of many diseases are being figured out by the PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The technique can help identify the sequence of previously unknown viruses related to those already known and thus give us a better understanding of the disease itself.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] If the procedure can be further simplified and sensitive non-radiometric detection systems can be developed, the PCR will assume a prominent place in the clinical laboratory for years to come.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] One major limitation of PCR is that prior information about the target sequence is necessary in order to generate the primers that will allow its selective amplification.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] The limitation is offset when using arbitrarily amplified DNA techniques such as DNA amplification fingerprinting (DAF) or randomly amplification of polymorphic DNA (RAPD).
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] These DNA profiling methods use arbitrary primers in PCR reactions that do not require sequence knowledge.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Like all enzymes, DNA polymerases are also prone to error, which in turn causes mutations in the PCR fragments that are generated.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Another limitation of PCR is that even the smallest amount of contaminating DNA can be amplified, resulting in misleading or ambiguous results.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] To minimize the chance of contamination, investigators should reserve separate rooms for reagent preparation, the PCR, and analysis of product.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Reagents should be dispensed into single-use aliquots.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Pipettors with disposable plungers and extra-long pipette tips should be routinely used.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] It is moreover recommended to ensure that the lab set-up follows a unidirectional workflow.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] No materials or reagents used in the PCR and analysis rooms should ever be taken into the PCR preparation room without thorough decontamination.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p01] Environmental samples that contain humic acids may inhibit PCR amplification and lead to inaccurate results.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] The heat-resistant enzymes that are a key component in polymerase chain reaction were discovered in the 1960s as a product of a microbial life form that lived in the superheated waters of Yellowstone's Mushroom Spring.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] A 1971 paper in the *Journal of Molecular Biology* by Kjell Kleppe and co-workers in the laboratory of H.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] Gobind Khorana first described a method of using an enzymatic assay to replicate a short DNA template with primers *in vitro*.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] However, this early manifestation of the basic PCR principle did not receive much attention at the time and the invention of the polymerase chain reaction in 1983 is generally credited to Kary Mullis.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] When Mullis developed the PCR in 1983, he was working in Emeryville, California for Cetus Corporation, one of the first biotechnology companies, where he was responsible for synthesizing short chains of DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] Mullis has written that he conceived the idea for PCR while cruising along the Pacific Coast Highway one night in his car.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] He was playing in his mind with a new way of analyzing changes (mutations) in DNA when he realized that he had instead invented a method of amplifying any DNA region through repeated cycles of duplication driven by DNA polymerase.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] In *Scientific American*, Mullis summarized the procedure: "Beginning with a single molecule of the genetic material DNA, the PCR can generate 100 billion similar molecules in an afternoon.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] It requires no more than a test tube, a few simple reagents, and a source of heat." DNA fingerprinting was first used for paternity testing in 1988.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] Mullis has credited his use of LSD as integral to his development of PCR: "Would I have invented PCR if I hadn't taken LSD?
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] Mullis and biochemist Michael Smith, who had developed other essential ways of manipulating DNA, were jointly awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1993, seven years after Mullis and his colleagues at Cetus first put his proposal to practice.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] At the core of the PCR method is the use of a suitable DNA polymerase able to withstand the high temperatures of >90 °C (194 °F) required for separation of the two DNA strands in the DNA double helix after each replication cycle.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] The DNA polymerases initially employed for in vitro experiments presaging PCR were unable to withstand these high temperatures.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] So the early procedures for DNA replication were very inefficient and time-consuming, and required large amounts of DNA polymerase and continuous handling throughout the process.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] The DNA polymerase isolated from *T. aquaticus* is stable at high temperatures remaining active even after DNA denaturation, thus obviating the need to add new DNA polymerase after each cycle.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] This allowed an automated thermocycler-based process for DNA amplification.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] The PCR technique was patented by Kary Mullis and assigned to Cetus Corporation, where Mullis worked when he invented the technique in 1983.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] The *Taq* polymerase enzyme was also covered by patents.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] There have been several lawsuits related to the technique brought by DuPont.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] The Swiss pharmaceutical company Hoffmann-La Roche purchased the rights to the patents in 1992.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] The last of the commercial PCR patents expired in 2017.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] A related patent battle over the *Taq* polymerase enzyme is still ongoing in several jurisdictions around the world between Roche and Promega.
[src:pcr-amplification/polymerase-chain-reaction-p02] The legal arguments have extended beyond the lives of the original PCR and *Taq* polymerase patents, which expired on 28 March 2005.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] A **primer** is a short, single-stranded nucleic acid used by all living organisms in the initiation of DNA synthesis.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] A synthetic primer is a type of **oligo**, short for oligonucleotide.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] DNA polymerases (responsible for DNA replication) are only capable of adding nucleotides to the 3'-end of an existing nucleic acid, requiring a primer be bound to the template before DNA polymerase can begin a complementary strand.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] DNA polymerase adds nucleotides after binding to the RNA primer and synthesizes the whole strand.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Later, the RNA strands must be removed accurately and replaced with DNA nucleotides.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] This forms a gap region known as a nick that is filled in using a ligase.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] The removal process of the RNA primer requires several enzymes, such as Fen1, Lig1, and others that work in coordination with DNA polymerase, to ensure the removal of the RNA nucleotides and the addition of DNA nucleotides.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Living organisms use solely RNA primers, while laboratory techniques in biochemistry and molecular biology that require in vitro DNA synthesis (such as DNA sequencing and polymerase chain reaction) usually use DNA primers, since they are more temperature stable.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Primers can be designed in laboratory for specific reactions such as polymerase chain reaction (PCR).
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] When designing PCR primers, there are specific measures that must be taken into consideration, like the melting temperature of the primers and the annealing temperature of the reaction itself.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] RNA primers are used by living organisms in the initiation of synthesizing a strand of DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] A class of enzymes called primases add a complementary RNA primer to the reading template *de novo* on both the leading and lagging strands.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Starting from the free 3'-OH of the primer, known as the primer terminus, a DNA polymerase can extend a newly synthesized strand.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] The leading strand in DNA replication is synthesized in one continuous piece moving with the replication fork, requiring only an initial RNA primer to begin synthesis.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] In the lagging strand, the template DNA runs in the 5′→3′ direction.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Since DNA polymerase cannot add bases in the 3′→5′ direction complementary to the template strand, DNA is synthesized 'backward' in short fragments moving away from the replication fork, known as Okazaki fragments.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Unlike in the leading strand, this method results in the repeated starting and stopping of DNA synthesis, requiring multiple RNA primers.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Along the DNA template, primase intersperses RNA primers that DNA polymerase uses to synthesize DNA from in the 5′→3′ direction.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Another example of primers being used to enable DNA synthesis is reverse transcription.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Reverse transcriptase is an enzyme that uses a template strand of RNA to synthesize a complementary strand of DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] The DNA polymerase component of reverse transcriptase requires an existing 3' end to begin synthesis.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] After the insertion of Okazaki fragments, the RNA primers are removed (the mechanism of removal differs between prokaryotes and eukaryotes) and replaced with new deoxyribonucleotides that fill the gaps where the RNA primer was present.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] DNA ligase then joins the fragmented strands together, completing the synthesis of the lagging strand.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] In prokaryotes, DNA polymerase I synthesizes the Okazaki fragment until it reaches the previous RNA primer.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Then the enzyme simultaneously acts as a 5′→3′ exonuclease, removing primer ribonucleotides in front and adding deoxyribonucleotides behind.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Both the activities of polymerization and excision of the RNA primer occur in the 5′→3′ direction, and polymerase I can do these activities simultaneously; this is known as "Nick Translation".
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Nick translation refers to the synchronized activity of polymerase I in removing the RNA primer and adding deoxyribonucleotides.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Later, a gap between the strands is formed called a nick, which is sealed using a DNA ligase.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] In eukaryotes the removal of RNA primers in the lagging strand is essential for the completion of replication.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Thus, as the lagging strand being synthesized by DNA polymerase δ in 5′→3′ direction, Okazaki fragments are formed, which are discontinuous strands of DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Then, when the DNA polymerase reaches to the 5' end of the RNA primer from the previous Okazaki fragment, it displaces the 5′ end of the primer into a single-stranded RNA flap which is removed by nuclease cleavage.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Cleavage of the RNA flaps involves three methods of primer removal.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] The first possibility of primer removal is by creating a short flap that is directly removed by flap structure-specific endonuclease 1 (FEN-1), which cleaves the 5' overhanging flap.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] This method is known as the short flap pathway of RNA primer removal.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] The second way to cleave a RNA primer is by degrading the RNA strand using a RNase, in eukaryotes it's known as the RNase H2.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] This enzyme degrades most of the annealed RNA primer, except the nucleotides close to the 5' end of the primer.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Thus, the remaining nucleotides are displayed into a flap that is cleaved off using FEN-1.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] The last possible method of removing RNA primer is known as the long flap pathway.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] In this pathway several enzymes are recruited to elongate the RNA primer and then cleave it off.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] The flaps are elongated by a 5' to 3' helicase, known as Pif1.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] After the addition of nucleotides to the flap by Pif1, the long flap is stabilized by the replication protein A (RPA).
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] The RPA-bound DNA inhibits the activity or recruitment of FEN1, as a result another nuclease must be recruited to cleave the flap.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] This second nuclease is DNA2 nuclease, which has a helicase-nuclease activity, that cleaves the long flap of RNA primer, which then leaves behind a couple of nucleotides that are cleaved by FEN1.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] At the end, when all the RNA primers have been removed, nicks form between the Okazaki fragments that are filled-in with deoxyribonucleotides using an enzyme known as ligase1, through a process called ligation.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Synthetic primers are chemically synthesized oligonucleotides, usually of DNA, which can be customized to anneal to a specific site on the template DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] In solution, the primer spontaneously hybridizes with the template through Watson-Crick base pairing before being extended by DNA polymerase.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Both Sanger sequencing and next-generation sequencing require primers to initiate the reaction.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] The polymerase chain reaction (PCR) uses a pair of custom primers to direct DNA elongation toward each other at opposite ends of the sequence being amplified.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] These primers are typically between 18 and 24 bases in length and are complementary to the specific upstream and downstream sites of the sequence being amplified.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Pairs of primers are designed to have similar melting temperatures since annealing during PCR occurs for both strands simultaneously.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] The melting temperature is not be either too much higher or lower than the reaction's annealing temperature.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] If annealing temperatures are too low, non-specific structures can form, reducing the efficiency of the reaction.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Additionally, primer sequences need to be chosen to uniquely select for a region of DNA, avoiding the possibility of hybridization to a similar sequence nearby.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] A commonly used method for selecting a primer site is BLAST search, whereby all the possible regions to which a primer may bind can be seen.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Both the nucleotide sequence as well as the primer itself can be BLAST searched.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] The free NCBI tool Primer-BLAST integrates primer design and BLAST search into one application, as do commercial software products such as ePrime and Beacon Designer.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] *In silico* PCR may be performed to evaluate the specificity of designed primers.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Selecting a specific region of DNA for primer binding requires some additional considerations.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Regions high in mononucleotide and dinucleotide repeats should be avoided, as loop formation can occur and contribute to mishybridization.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Primers that are complementary to each other can lead to the formation of primer-dimers, lowering the efficiency of the desired reaction.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Primers that are able to anneal to themselves can form internal hairpins and loops that hinder hybridization with the template DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] When designing primers, additional nucleotide bases can be added to the back ends of each primer, resulting in a customized cap sequence on each end of the amplified region.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] One application for this practice is for use in TA cloning, a special subcloning technique similar to PCR, where efficiency can be increased by adding AG tails to the 5′ and the 3′ ends.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Some situations may call for the use of *degenerate primers.* These are mixtures of primers that are similar, but not identical.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] These may be convenient when amplifying the same gene from different organisms, as the sequences are probably similar but not identical.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] This technique is useful because the genetic code itself is degenerate, meaning several different codons can code for the same amino acid.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] This allows different organisms to have a significantly different genetic sequence that code for a highly similar protein.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] For this reason, degenerate primers are also used when primer design is based on protein sequence, as the specific sequence of codons are not known.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Therefore, primer sequence corresponding to the amino acid isoleucine might be "ATH", where A stands for adenine, T for thymine, and H for adenine, thymine, or cytosine, according to the genetic code for each codon, using the IUPAC symbols for degenerate bases.
[src:pcr-amplification/primer-molecular-biology] Degenerate primers may not perfectly hybridize with a target sequence, which can greatly reduce the specificity of the PCR amplification.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] A **real-time polymerase chain reaction** (**real-time PCR**, or **qPCR** when used quantitatively) is a laboratory technique of molecular biology based on the polymerase chain reaction (PCR).
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] It monitors the amplification of a targeted DNA molecule during the PCR (i.e., in real time), not at its end, as in conventional PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Real-time PCR can be used quantitatively and semi-quantitatively (i.e., above/below a certain amount of DNA molecules).
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The acronym "RT-PCR" commonly denotes reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction and not real-time PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Cells in all organisms regulate gene expression by turnover of gene transcripts (single stranded RNA): The amount of an expressed gene in a cell can be measured by the number of copies of an RNA transcript of that gene present in a sample.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] In order to robustly detect and quantify gene expression from small amounts of RNA, amplification of the gene transcript is necessary.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The polymerase chain reaction (PCR) is a common method for amplifying DNA; for RNA-based PCR the RNA sample is first reverse-transcribed to complementary DNA (cDNA) with reverse transcriptase.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] In order to amplify small amounts of DNA, the same methodology is used as in conventional PCR using a DNA template, at least one pair of specific primers, deoxyribonucleotide triphosphates, a suitable buffer solution and a thermo-stable DNA polymerase.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] A substance marked with a fluorophore is added to this mixture in a thermal cycler that contains sensors for measuring the fluorescence of the fluorophore after it has been excited at the required wavelength allowing the generation rate to be measured for one or more specific products.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] This allows the rate of generation of the amplified product to be measured at each PCR cycle.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The data thus generated can be analysed by computer software to calculate *relative gene expression* (or *mRNA copy number*) in several samples.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Quantitative PCR can also be applied to the detection and quantification of DNA in samples to determine the presence and abundance of a particular DNA sequence in these samples.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] This measurement is made after each amplification cycle, and this is the reason why this method is called real time PCR (that is, immediate or simultaneous PCR).
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Quantitative PCR and DNA microarray are modern methodologies for studying gene expression.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Older methods were used to measure mRNA abundance: differential display, RNase protection assay and northern blot.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Northern blotting is often used to estimate the expression level of a gene by visualizing the abundance of its mRNA transcript in a sample.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] In this method, purified RNA is separated by agarose gel electrophoresis, transferred to a solid matrix (such as a nylon membrane), and probed with a specific DNA or RNA probe that is complementary to the gene of interest.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Although this technique is still used to assess gene expression, it requires relatively large amounts of RNA and provides only qualitative or semi quantitative information of mRNA levels.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Estimation errors arising from variations in the quantification method can be the result of DNA integrity, enzyme efficiency and many other factors.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] For this reason a number of standardization systems (often called normalization methods) have been developed.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Some have been developed for quantifying total gene expression, but the most common are aimed at quantifying the specific gene being studied in relation to another gene called a normalizing gene, which is selected for its almost constant level of expression.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] These genes are often selected from housekeeping genes as their functions related to basic cellular survival normally imply constitutive gene expression.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] This enables researchers to report a ratio for the expression of the genes of interest divided by the expression of the selected normalizer, thereby allowing comparison of the former without actually knowing its absolute level of expression.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The most commonly used normalizing genes are those that code for the following molecules: tubulin, glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase, albumin, cyclophilin, and ribosomal RNAs.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Real-time PCR is carried out in a thermal cycler with the capacity to illuminate each sample with a beam of light of at least one specified wavelength and detect the fluorescence emitted by the excited fluorophore.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The thermal cycler is also able to rapidly heat and chill samples, thereby taking advantage of the physicochemical properties of the nucleic acids and DNA polymerase.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The PCR process generally consists of a series of temperature changes that are repeated 25–50 times.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Due to the small size of the fragments the last step is usually omitted in this type of PCR as the enzyme is able to replicate the DNA amplicon during the change between the alignment stage and the denaturing stage.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] In addition, in four-step PCR the fluorescence is measured during short temperature phases lasting only a few seconds in each cycle, with a temperature of, for example, 80 °C, in order to reduce the signal caused by the presence of primer dimers when a non-specific dye is used.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The temperatures and the timings used for each cycle depend on a wide variety of parameters, such as: the enzyme used to synthesize the DNA, the concentration of divalent ions and deoxyribonucleotide triphosphates (dNTPs) in the reaction and the bonding temperature of the primers.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Real-time PCR technique can be classified by the chemistry used to detect the PCR product, specific or non-specific fluorochromes.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] A DNA-binding dye binds to all double-stranded (ds) DNA in PCR, increasing the fluorescence quantum yield of the dye.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] An increase in DNA product during PCR therefore leads to an increase in fluorescence intensity measured at each cycle.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] However, dsDNA dyes such as SYBR Green will bind to all dsDNA PCR products, including nonspecific PCR products (such as primer dimer).
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] This can potentially interfere with, or prevent, accurate monitoring of the intended target sequence.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] In real-time PCR with dsDNA dyes the reaction is prepared as usual, with the addition of fluorescent dsDNA dye.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Then the reaction is run in a real-time PCR instrument, and after each cycle, the intensity of fluorescence is measured with a detector; the dye only fluoresces when bound to the dsDNA (i.e., the PCR product).
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] This method has the advantage of only needing a pair of primers to carry out the amplification, which keeps costs down; multiple target sequences can be monitored in a tube by using different types of dyes.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Fluorescent reporter probes detect only the DNA containing the sequence complementary to the probe; therefore, use of the reporter probe significantly increases specificity, and enables performing the technique even in the presence of other dsDNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Using different-coloured labels, fluorescent probes can be used in multiplex assays for monitoring several target sequences in the same tube.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The specificity of fluorescent reporter probes also prevents interference of measurements caused by primer dimers, which are undesirable potential by-products in PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] However, fluorescent reporter probes do not prevent the inhibitory effect of the primer dimers, which may depress accumulation of the desired products in the reaction.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The method relies on a DNA-based probe with a fluorescent reporter at one end and a quencher of fluorescence at the opposite end of the probe.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] An increase in the product targeted by the reporter probe at each PCR cycle therefore causes a proportional increase in fluorescence due to the breakdown of the probe and release of the reporter.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] As the reaction commences, during the annealing stage of the PCR both probe and primers anneal to the DNA target.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Polymerisation of a new DNA strand is initiated from the primers, and once the polymerase reaches the probe, its 5'-3'-exonuclease degrades the probe, physically separating the fluorescent reporter from the quencher, resulting in an increase in fluorescence.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Fluorescence is detected and measured in a real-time PCR machine, and its geometric increase corresponding to exponential increase of the product is used to determine the quantification cycle (Cq) in each reaction.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Real-time PCR permits the identification of specific, amplified DNA fragments using analysis of their melting temperature (also called *Tm* value, from m*elting* t*emperature*).
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The method used is usually PCR with double-stranded DNA-binding dyes as reporters and the dye used is usually SYBR Green.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The DNA melting temperature is specific to the amplified fragment.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The results of this technique are obtained by comparing the dissociation curves of the analysed DNA samples.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Unlike conventional PCR, this method avoids the previous use of electrophoresis techniques to demonstrate the results of all the samples.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] This is because, despite being a kinetic technique, quantitative PCR is usually evaluated at a distinct end point.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The technique therefore usually provides more rapid results and/or uses fewer reactants than electrophoresis.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] If subsequent electrophoresis is required it is only necessary to test those samples that real time PCR has shown to be doubtful and/or to ratify the results for samples that have tested positive for a specific determinant.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Unlike end point PCR (conventional PCR), real time PCR allows monitoring of the desired product at any point in the amplification process by measuring fluorescence (in real time frame, measurement is made of its level over a given threshold).
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] A commonly employed method of DNA quantification by real-time PCR relies on plotting fluorescence against the number of cycles on a logarithmic scale.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] A threshold for detection of DNA-based fluorescence is set 3–5 times of the standard deviation of the signal noise above background.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The number of cycles at which the fluorescence exceeds the threshold is called the threshold cycle (Ct) or, according to the MIQE guidelines, quantification cycle (Cq).
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Using this method, the greater the amount of starting mRNA, the lower the Cq.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] During the exponential amplification phase, the quantity of the target DNA template (amplicon) doubles every cycle.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] For example, a DNA sample whose Cq precedes that of another sample by 3 cycles contained 23 = 8 times more template.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] However, the efficiency of amplification is often variable among primers and templates.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Therefore, the efficiency of a primer-template combination is assessed in a titration experiment with serial dilutions of DNA template to create a standard curve of the change in (Cq) with each dilution.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The slope of the linear regression is then used to determine the efficiency of amplification, which is 100% if a dilution of 1:2 results in a (Cq) difference of 1.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The cycle threshold method makes several assumptions of reaction mechanism and has a reliance on data from low signal-to-noise regions of the amplification profile that can introduce substantial variance during the data analysis.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] To quantify gene expression, the (Cq) for an RNA or DNA from the gene of interest is subtracted from the (Cq) of RNA/DNA from a housekeeping gene in the same sample to normalize for variation in the amount and quality of RNA between different samples.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] This normalization procedure is commonly called the *ΔCt-method* and permits comparison of expression of a gene of interest among different samples.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] However, for such comparison, expression of the normalizing reference gene needs to be very similar across all the samples.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Choosing a reference gene fulfilling this criterion is therefore of high importance, and often challenging, because only very few genes show equal levels of expression across a range of different conditions or tissues.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Although cycle threshold analysis is integrated with many commercial software systems, there are more accurate and reliable methods of analysing amplification profile data that should be considered in cases where reproducibility is a concern.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Mechanism-based qPCR quantification methods have also been suggested, and have the advantage that they do not require a standard curve for quantification.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Methods such as MAK2 have been shown to have equal or better quantitative performance to standard curve methods.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] These mechanism-based methods use knowledge about the polymerase amplification process to generate estimates of the original sample concentration.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] An extension of this approach includes an accurate model of the entire PCR reaction profile, which allows for the use of high signal-to-noise data and the ability to validate data quality prior to analysis.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] MAK2 assumes constant amplification efficiency during the PCR reaction.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] However, theoretical analysis of polymerase chain reaction, from which MAK2 was derived, has revealed that amplification efficiency is not constant throughout PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] While MAK2 quantification provides reliable estimates of target DNA concentration in a sample under normal qPCR conditions, MAK2 does not reliably quantify target concentration for qPCR assays with competimeters.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] There are numerous applications for quantitative polymerase chain reaction in the laboratory.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] It is commonly used for both diagnostic and basic research.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Uses of the technique in industry include the quantification of microbial load in foods or on vegetable matter, the detection of GMOs (genetically modified organisms) and the quantification and genotyping of human viral pathogens.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Quantifying gene expression by traditional DNA detection methods is unreliable.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Detection of mRNA on a northern blot or PCR products on a gel or Southern blot does not allow precise quantification.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] For example, over the 20–40 cycles of a typical PCR, the amount of DNA product reaches a plateau that is not directly correlated with the amount of target DNA in the initial PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Real-time PCR can be used to quantify nucleic acids by two common methods: relative quantification and absolute quantification.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Absolute quantification gives the exact number of target DNA molecules by comparison with DNA standards using a calibration curve.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] It is therefore essential that the PCR of the sample and the standard have the same amplification efficiency.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Relative quantification is based on internal reference genes to determine fold-differences in expression of the target gene.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The quantification is expressed as the change in expression levels of mRNA interpreted as complementary DNA (cDNA, generated by reverse transcription of mRNA).
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Relative quantification is easier to carry out as it does not require a calibration curve as the amount of the studied gene is compared to the amount of a control reference gene.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] As the units used to express the results of relative quantification are unimportant the results can be compared across a number of different RTqPCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The reason for using one or more housekeeping genes is to correct non-specific variation, such as the differences in the quantity and quality of RNA used, which can affect the efficiency of reverse transcription and therefore that of the whole PCR process.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] However, the most crucial aspect of the process is that the reference gene must be stable.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The selection of these reference genes was traditionally carried out in molecular biology using qualitative or semi-quantitative studies such as the visual examination of RNA gels, northern blot densitometry or semi-quantitative PCR (PCR mimics).
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Now, in the genome era, it is possible to carry out a more detailed estimate for many organisms using transcriptomic technologies.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] However, research has shown that amplification of the majority of reference genes used in quantifying the expression of mRNA varies according to experimental conditions.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] It is therefore necessary to carry out an initial statistically sound methodological study in order to select the most suitable reference gene.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] A number of statistical algorithms have been developed that can detect which gene or genes are most suitable for use under given conditions.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Those like geNORM or BestKeeper can compare pairs or geometric means for a matrix of different reference genes and tissues.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The entire qPCR analysis workflow with proper error propagations is implemented in GenEx.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Diagnostic qualitative PCR is applied to rapidly detect nucleic acids that are diagnostic of, for example, infectious diseases, cancer and genetic abnormalities.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The introduction of qualitative PCR assays to the clinical microbiology laboratory has significantly improved the diagnosis of infectious diseases, and is deployed as a tool to detect newly emerging diseases, such as new strains of flu and coronavirus, in diagnostic tests.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Quantitative PCR is also used by microbiologists working in the fields of food safety, food spoilage and fermentation and for the microbial risk assessment of water quality (drinking and recreational waters) and in public health protection.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] qPCR may also be used to amplify taxonomic or functional markers of genes in DNA taken from environmental samples.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Markers are represented by genetic fragments of DNA or complementary DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] By amplifying a certain genetic element, one can quantify the amount of the element in the sample prior to amplification.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Using taxonomic markers (ribosomal genes) and qPCR can help determine the amount of microorganisms in a sample, and can identify different families, genera, or species based on the specificity of the marker.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Using functional markers (protein-coding genes) can show gene expression within a community, which may reveal information about the environment.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The agricultural industry is constantly striving to produce plant propagules or seedlings that are free of pathogens in order to prevent economic losses and safeguard health.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Systems have been developed that allow detection of small amounts of the DNA of *Phytophthora ramorum*, an oomycete that kills oaks and other species, mixed in with the DNA of the host plant.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Discrimination between the DNA of the pathogen and the plant is based on the amplification of ITS sequences, spacers located in ribosomal RNA gene's coding area, which are characteristic for each taxon.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Field-based versions of this technique have also been developed for identifying the same pathogen.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] qPCR using reverse transcription (RT-qPCR) can be used to detect GMOs given its sensitivity and dynamic range in detecting DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Alternatives such as DNA or protein analysis are usually less sensitive.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Specific primers are used that amplify not the transgene but the promoter, terminator or even intermediate sequences used during the process of engineering the vector.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] As the process of creating a transgenic plant normally leads to the insertion of more than one copy of the transgene its quantity is also commonly assessed.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] This is often carried out by relative quantification using a control gene from the treated species that is only present as a single copy.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Viruses can be present in humans due to direct infection or co-infections which makes diagnosis difficult using classical techniques and can result in an incorrect prognosis and treatment.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The use of qPCR allows both the quantification and genotyping (characterization of the strain, carried out using melting curves) of a virus such as the hepatitis B virus.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] The degree of infection, quantified as the copies of the viral genome per unit of the patient's tissue, is relevant in many cases; for example, the probability that the type 1 herpes simplex virus reactivates is related to the number of infected neurons in the ganglia.
[src:pcr-amplification/real-time-polymerase-chain-reaction] Real-time PCR has also brought the quantization of human cytomegalovirus (CMV) which is seen in patients who are immunosuppressed following solid organ or bone marrow transplantation.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The close association between RT-PCR and qPCR has led to metonymic use of the term qPCR to mean RT-PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Such use may be confusing, as RT-PCR can be used without qPCR, for example to enable molecular cloning, sequencing or simple detection of RNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Conversely, qPCR may be used without RT-PCR, for example, to quantify the copy number of a specific piece of DNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The combined RT-PCR and qPCR technique has been described as quantitative RT-PCR or real-time RT-PCR (sometimes even called quantitative real-time RT-PCR), has been variously abbreviated as qRT-PCR, RT-qPCR, RRT-PCR, and rRT-PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Not all authors, especially earlier ones, use this convention and the reader should be cautious when following links.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] RT-PCR has been used to indicate both real-time PCR (qPCR) and reverse transcription PCR (RT-PCR).
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Since its introduction in 1977, Northern blot has been used extensively for RNA quantification despite its shortcomings: (a) time-consuming technique, (b) requires a large quantity of RNA for detection, and (c) quantitatively inaccurate in the low abundance of RNA content.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] However, since PCR was invented by Kary Mullis in 1983, RT PCR has since displaced Northern blot as the method of choice for RNA detection and quantification.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Due to its simplicity, specificity and sensitivity, RT-PCR is used in a wide range of applications from experiments as simple as quantification of yeast cells in wine to more complex uses as diagnostic tools for detecting infectious agents such as the avian flu virus and SARS-CoV-2.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] In RT-PCR, the RNA template is first converted into a complementary DNA (cDNA) using a reverse transcriptase (RT).
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The cDNA is then used as a template for exponential amplification using PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The quantification of mRNA using RT-PCR can be achieved as either a one-step or a two-step reaction.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The difference between the two approaches lies in the number of tubes used when performing the procedure.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The two-step reaction requires that the reverse transcriptase reaction and PCR amplification be performed in separate tubes.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The disadvantage of the two-step approach is susceptibility to contamination due to more frequent sample handling.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] On the other hand, the entire reaction from cDNA synthesis to PCR amplification occurs in a single tube in the one-step approach.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The one-step approach is thought to minimize experimental variation by containing all of the enzymatic reactions in a single environment.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] It eliminates the steps of pipetting cDNA product, which is labor-intensive and prone to contamination, to PCR reaction.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The further use of inhibitor-tolerant thermostable DNA polymerases, polymerase enhancers with an optimized one-step RT-PCR condition, supports the reverse transcription of the RNA from unpurified or crude samples, such as whole blood and serum.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] However, the starting RNA templates are prone to degradation in the one-step approach, and the use of this approach is not recommended when repeated assays from the same sample is required.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Additionally, the one-step approach is reported to be less accurate compared to the two-step approach.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] It is also the preferred method of analysis when using DNA binding dyes such as SYBR Green since the elimination of primer-dimers can be achieved through a simple change in the melting temperature.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Nevertheless, the one-step approach is a relatively convenient solution for the rapid detection of target RNA directly in biosensing.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Quantification of RT-PCR products can largely be divided into two categories: end-point and real-time.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The use of end-point RT-PCR is preferred for measuring gene expression changes in small number of samples, but the real-time RT-PCR has become the gold standard method for validating quantitative results obtained from array analyses or gene expression changes on a global scale.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The measurement approaches of end-point RT-PCR requires the detection of gene expression levels by the use of fluorescent dyes like ethidium bromide, P32 labeling of PCR products using phosphorimager, or by scintillation counting.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] End-point RT-PCR is commonly achieved using three different methods: relative, competitive and comparative.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Relative quantifications of RT-PCR involves the co-amplification of an internal control simultaneously with the gene of interest.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The internal control is used to normalize the samples.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Once normalized, a direct comparison of relative transcript abundances across multiple samples of mRNA can be made.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] One precaution to note is that the internal control must be chosen so that it is not affected by the experimental treatment.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The expression level should be constant across all samples and with the mRNA of interest for the results to be accurate and meaningful.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Because the quantification of the results are analyzed by comparing the linear range of the target and control amplification, it is crucial to take into consideration the starting target molecules concentration and their amplification rate prior to starting the analysis.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The results of the analysis are expressed as the ratios of gene signal to internal control signal, which the values can then be used for the comparison between the samples in the estimation of relative target RNA expression.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Competitive RT-PCR technique is used for absolute quantification.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] It involves the use of a synthetic “competitor” RNA that can be distinguished from the target RNA by a small difference in size or sequence.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] It is important for the design of the synthetic RNA be identical in sequence but slightly shorter than the target RNA for accurate results.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Once designed and synthesized, a known amount of the competitor RNA is added to experimental samples and is co-amplified with the target using RT-PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Then, a concentration curve of the competitor RNA is produced and it is used to compare the RT-PCR signals produced from the endogenous transcripts to determine the amount of target present in the sample.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Comparative RT-PCR is similar to the competitive RT-PCR in that the target RNA competes for amplification reagents within a single reaction with an internal standard of unrelated sequence.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Once the reaction is complete, the results are compared to an external standard curve to determine the target RNA concentration.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The emergence of novel fluorescent DNA labeling techniques in the past few years has enabled the analysis and detection of PCR products in real-time and has consequently led to the widespread adoption of real-time RT-PCR for the analysis of gene expression.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Not only is real-time RT-PCR now the method of choice for quantification of gene expression, it is also the preferred method of obtaining results from array analyses and gene expressions on a global scale.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Currently, there are four different fluorescent DNA probes available for the real-time RT-PCR detection of PCR products: SYBR Green, TaqMan, molecular beacons, and scorpion probes.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] All of these probes allow the detection of PCR products by generating a fluorescent signal.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] When the SYBR Green binds to the double-stranded DNA of the PCR products, it will emit light upon excitation.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The intensity of the fluorescence increases as the PCR products accumulate.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] This technique is easy to use since designing of probes is not necessary given lack of specificity of its binding.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] However, since the dye does not discriminate the double-stranded DNA from the PCR products and those from the primer-dimers, overestimation of the target concentration is a common problem.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Where accurate quantification is an absolute necessity, further assay for the validation of results must be performed.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Nevertheless, among the real-time RT-PCR product detection methods, SYBR Green is the most economical and easiest to use.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] TaqMan probes are oligonucleotides that have a fluorescent probe attached to the 5' end and a quencher to the 3' end.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] and as polymerase replicates the template with TaqMan bound, it also cleaves the fluorescent probe due to polymerase 5'- nuclease activity.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Because the close proximity between the quench molecule and the fluorescent probe normally prevents fluorescence from being detected through FRET, the decoupling results in the increase of intensity of fluorescence proportional to the number of the probe cleavage cycles.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Although well-designed TaqMan probes produce accurate real-time RT-PCR results, it is expensive and time-consuming to synthesize when separate probes must be made for each mRNA target analyzed.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Additionally, these probes are light sensitive and must be carefully frozen as aliquots to prevent degradation.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Similar to the TaqMan probes, molecular beacons also make use of FRET detection with fluorescent probes attached to the 5' end and a quencher attached to the 3' end of an oligonucleotide substrate.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] However, whereas the TaqMan fluorescent probes are cleaved during amplification, molecular beacon probes remain intact and rebind to a new target during each reaction cycle.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] When free in solution, the close proximity of the fluorescent probe and the quencher molecule prevents fluorescence through FRET.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] However, when molecular beacon probes hybridize to a target, the fluorescent dye and the quencher are separated resulting in the emittance of light upon excitation.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] As is with the TaqMan probes, molecular beacons are expensive to synthesize and require separate probes for each RNA target.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The scorpion probes, like molecular beacons, will not be fluorescent active in an unhybridized state, again, due to the fluorescent probe on the 5' end being quenched by the moiety on the 3' end of an oligonucleotide.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] With Scorpions, however, the 3' end also contains sequence that is complementary to the extension product of the primer on the 5' end.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] When the Scorpion extension binds to its complement on the amplicon, the Scorpion structure opens, prevents FRET, and enables the fluorescent signal to be measured.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] TaqMan probes, molecular beacons, and scorpions allow the concurrent measurement of PCR products in a single tube.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] This is possible because each of the different fluorescent dyes can be associated with a specific emission spectra.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Two strategies are commonly employed to quantify the results obtained by real-time RT-PCR; the standard curve method and the comparative threshold method.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The exponential amplification via reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction provides for a highly sensitive technique in which a very low copy number of RNA molecules can be detected.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] RT-PCR is widely used in the diagnosis of genetic diseases and, semiquantitatively, in the determination of the abundance of specific different RNA molecules within a cell or tissue as a measure of gene expression.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] RT-PCR is commonly used in research methods to measure gene expression.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] For example, Lin et al. used qRT-PCR to measure expression of Gal genes in yeast cells.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] First, Lin et al. engineered a mutation of a protein suspected to participate in the regulation of Gal genes.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] This mutation was hypothesized to selectively abolish Gal expression.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] To confirm this, gene expression levels of yeast cells containing this mutation were analyzed using qRT-PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The researchers were able to conclusively determine that the mutation of this regulatory protein reduced Gal expression.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Northern blot analysis is used to study the RNA's gene expression further.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] RT-PCR can also be very useful in the insertion of eukaryotic genes into prokaryotes.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] When these genes are expressed in prokaryotic cells for the sake of protein production or purification, the RNA produced directly from transcription need not undergo splicing as the transcript contains only exons.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] (Prokaryotes, such as E. coli, lack the mRNA splicing mechanism of eukaryotes).
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] RT-PCR can be used to diagnose genetic disease such as Lesch–Nyhan syndrome.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Scientists are working on ways to use RT-PCR in cancer detection to help improve prognosis, and monitor response to therapy.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Circulating tumor cells produce unique mRNA transcripts depending on the type of cancer.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The goal is to determine which mRNA transcripts serve as the best biomarkers for a particular cancer cell type and then analyze its expression levels with RT-PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] RT-PCR is commonly used in studying the genomes of viruses whose genomes are composed of RNA, such as Influenzavirus A, retroviruses like HIV and SARS-CoV-2.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] PCR tests can be used for early detection of DNA-based pathogens through the amplification of a pathogen's DNA, even before the host begins producing antibodies.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] RT-PCR allows this process to be applied to RNA viruses.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] RT-PCR tests are best known for their use in COVID-19 testing but have also been used to diagnose diseases such as Ebola, Zika, MERS, SARS, and influenza.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Despite its major advantages, RT-PCR is not without drawbacks.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The exponential growth of the reverse transcribed complementary DNA (cDNA) during the multiple cycles of PCR produces inaccurate end point quantification due to the difficulty in maintaining linearity.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] In order to provide accurate detection and quantification of RNA content in a sample, qRT-PCR was developed using fluorescence-based modification to monitor the amplification products during each cycle of PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The extreme sensitivity of the technique can be a double-edged sword since even the slightest DNA contamination can lead to undesirable results.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] A simple method for elimination of false positive results is to include anchors, or tags, to the 5' region of a gene specific primer.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Additionally, planning and design of quantification studies can be technically challenging due to the existence of numerous sources of variation including template concentration and amplification efficiency.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Spiking in a known quantity of RNA into a sample, adding a series of RNA dilutions generating a standard curve, and adding in a no template copy sample (no cDNA) may used as controls.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] RT-PCR can be carried out by the one-step RT-PCR protocol or the two-step RT-PCR protocol.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] One-step RT-PCR subjects mRNA targets (up to 6 kb) to reverse transcription followed by PCR amplification in a single test tube.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Using intact, high-quality RNA and a sequence-specific primer will produce the best results.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Once a one-step RT-PCR kit with a mix of reverse transcriptase, Taq DNA polymerase, and a proofreading polymerase is selected and all necessary materials and equipment are obtained a reaction mix is to be prepared.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The reaction mix includes dNTPs, primers, template RNA, necessary enzymes, and a buffer solution.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The reaction mix is added to a PCR tube for each reaction, followed by template RNA.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The PCR tubes are then placed in a thermal cycler to begin cycling.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] In the first cycle, the synthesis of cDNA occurs.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The second cycle is the initial denaturation wherein reverse transcriptase is inactivated.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The remaining 40-50 cycles are the amplification, which includes denaturation, annealing, and elongation.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] When amplification is complete, the RT-PCR products can be analyzed with gel electrophoresis.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Two-step RT-PCR, as the name implies, occurs in two steps.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] First the reverse transcription and then the PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] This method is more sensitive than the one-step method.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Kits are also useful for two-step RT-PCR.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Just as for one-step PCR, use only intact, high-quality RNA for the best results.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The primer for two-step PCR does not have to be sequence-specific.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] First combine template RNA, primer, dNTP mix, and nuclease-free water in a PCR tube.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Then, add an RNase inhibitor and reverse transcriptase to the PCR tube.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Next, place the PCR tube into a thermal cycler for one cycle wherein annealing, extending, and inactivating of reverse transcriptase occurs.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Finally, proceed directly to step two which is PCR, or store product on ice until PCR can be performed.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Add master mix which contains buffer, dNTP mix, MgCl2, Taq polymerase, and nuclease-free water to each PCR tube.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Then add the necessary primer to the tubes.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Next, place the PCR tubes in a thermal cycler for 30 cycles of the amplification program.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] This includes denaturation, annealing, and elongation.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The products of RT-PCR can be analyzed with gel electrophoresis.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Quantitative RT-PCR assay is considered to be the gold standard for measuring the number of copies of specific cDNA targets in a sample but it is poorly standardized.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] As a result, while there are numerous publications utilizing the technique, many provide inadequate experimental detail and use unsuitable data analysis to draw inappropriate conclusions.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Due to the inherent variability in the quality of any quantitative PCR data, not only do reviewers have a difficult time evaluating these manuscripts, but the studies also become impossible to replicate.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The MIQE guidelines describe the minimum information necessary for evaluating quantitative PCR experiments that should be required for publication to encourage better experimental practice and ensuring the relevance, accuracy, correct interpretation, and repeatability of quantitative PCR data.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] It also proposes that commercially derived terms like *TaqMan probes* should not be used, but instead referred to as *hydrolysis probes*.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The guideline consists of the following elements: 1) experimental design, 2) sample, 3) nucleic acid extraction, 4) reverse transcription, 5) qPCR target information, 6) oligonucleotides, 7) protocol, 8) validation, and 9) data analysis.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Specific items within each element carry a label of either E (essential) or D (desirable).
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Those labeled E are considered critical and indispensable while those labeled D are considered peripheral yet important for best practices.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] Together they support training at Precision BioAnalytics at GoCo Health Innovation City in Gothenburg, Sweden, after discontinuing the courses at TATAA Biocenter after the overtake by Care Equity.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] In 2023, researchers developed a working prototype of an RT-LAMP lab-on-a-chip system, which provided results for SARS-CoV-2 tests within three minutes.
[src:pcr-amplification/reverse-transcription-polymerase-chain-reaction] The technology integrates microfluidic channels into printed circuit boards with, which may enable low-cost mass production.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] One of *Taq'*s drawbacks is its lack of 3' to 5' exonuclease proofreading activity resulting in relatively low replication fidelity.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Originally its error rate was measured at about 1 in 9,000 nucleotides.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Some thermostable DNA polymerases have been isolated from other thermophilic bacteria and archaea, such as *Pfu* DNA polymerase, possessing a proofreading activity, and are being used instead of (or in combination with) *Taq* for high-fidelity amplification.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Fidelity can vary widely between Taqs, which has profound effects in downstream sequencing applications.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] In the early 1980s, Kary Mullis was working at Cetus Corporation on the application of synthetic DNAs to biotechnology.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] He was familiar with the use of DNA oligonucleotides as probes for binding to target DNA strands, as well as their use as primers for DNA sequencing and cDNA synthesis.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] In 1983, he began using two primers, one to hybridize to each strand of a target DNA, and adding DNA polymerase to the reaction.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] This led to exponential DNA replication, greatly amplifying discrete segments of DNA between the primers.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] However, after each round of replication the mixture needs to be heated above 90 °C to denature the newly formed DNA, allowing the strands to separate and act as templates in the next round of amplification.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] This heating step also inactivates the DNA polymerase that was in use before the discovery of *Taq* polymerase, the Klenow fragment (sourced from *E. coli*).
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] *Taq* polymerase is well-suited for this application because it is able to withstand the temperature of 95 °C which is required for DNA strand separation without denaturing.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Use of the thermostable *Taq* enables running the PCR at high temperature (~60 °C and above), which facilitates high specificity of the primers and reduces the production of nonspecific products, such as primer dimer.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Also, use of a thermostable polymerase eliminates the need to add new enzyme to each round of thermocycling.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] A single closed tube in a relatively simple machine can be used to carry out the entire process.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Thus, the use of *Taq* polymerase was the key idea that made PCR applicable to a large variety of molecular biology problems concerning DNA analysis.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Hoffmann-La Roche eventually bought the PCR and *Taq* patents from Cetus for $330 million, from which it may have received up to $2 billion in royalties.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] In 1989, Science Magazine named *Taq* polymerase its first "Molecule of the Year".
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Kary Mullis received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1993, the only one awarded for research performed at a biotechnology company.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] By the early 1990s, the PCR technique with *Taq* polymerase was being used in many areas, including basic molecular biology research, clinical testing, and forensics.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] It also began to find a pressing application in direct detection of the HIV in AIDS.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] District Judge Vaughn Walker ruled that the 1990 patent involving *Taq* polymerase was issued, in part, on misleading information and false claims by scientists with Cetus Corporation.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] The ruling supported a challenge by Promega Corporation against Hoffman-La Roche, which purchased the *Taq* patents in 1991.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Judge Walker cited previous discoveries by other laboratories, including the laboratory of John Trela at the University of Cincinnati department of biological sciences, as the basis for the ruling.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Unlike the same domain in *E. coli*, which would degrade primers and must be removed by digestion for PCR use, this domain is not said to degrade the primer.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] This activity is used in the TaqMan probe: as the daughter strands are formed, the probes complementary to the template come in contact with the polymerase and are cleaved into fluorescent pieces.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] A site-directed mutagenesis experiment that improves the vestigial 3'-5' exonuclease activity by a factor of 2 has been reported, but it was never reported whether doing so decreases the error rate.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Following a similar line of thought, chimera proteins have been made by cherry-picking domains from *E. coli*, *Taq*, and *T. neapolitana* polymerase I.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Swapping out the vestigial domain for a functional one from *E. coli* created a protein with proof-reading ability but a lower optimal temperature and low thermostability.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Versions of the polymerase without the 5'-3' exonuclease domain has been produced, among which *Klentaq* or the *Stoffel* fragment are best known.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] The complete lack of exonuclease activity make these variants suitable for primers that exhibit secondary structure as well as for copying circular molecules.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Because of the improvements *Taq* polymerase provided in PCR DNA replication: higher specificity, fewer nonspecific products, and simpler processes and equipment, it has been instrumental in the efforts made to detect diseases.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] It has served an essential role in the detection of many of the world's worst diseases, including: tuberculosis, streptococcal pharyngitis, atypical pneumonia, AIDS, measles, hepatitis, and ulcerative urogenital infections.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] PCR, the method used to recreate copies of specific DNA samples, makes disease detection possible by targeting a specific DNA sequence of a targeted pathogen from a patient's sample and amplifying trace amounts of the indicative sequences by copying them up to billions of times.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Although this is the most accurate method of disease detection, especially for HIV, it is not performed as often as alternative, inferior tests because of the relatively high cost, labor, and time required.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] The reliance upon *Taq* polymerase as a catalyst for the PCR replication process has been highlighted during the COVID-19 Pandemic of 2020.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Shortages of the necessary enzyme have impaired the ability of countries worldwide to produce test kits for the virus.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Without *Taq* polymerase, the disease detection process is much slower and tedious.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Despite the advantages of using *Taq* polymerase in PCR disease detection, the enzyme is not without its shortcomings.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Retroviral diseases (HIV, HTLV-1, and HTLV-II) often include mutations from guanine to adenine in their genome.
[src:pcr-amplification/taq-polymerase] Mutations such as these are what allow PCR tests to detect the diseases but *Taq* polymerase’s relatively low fidelity rate makes the same G-to-A mutation occur and possibly yield a false positive test result.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] The **thermal cycler** (also known as a **thermocycler**, **PCR machine** or **DNA amplifier**) is a laboratory apparatus most commonly used to amplify segments of DNA via the polymerase chain reaction (PCR).
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] Thermal cyclers may also be used in laboratories to facilitate other temperature-sensitive reactions, including restriction enzyme digestion or rapid diagnostics.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] The device has a *thermal block* with holes where tubes holding the reaction mixtures can be inserted.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] The cycler then raises and lowers the temperature of the block in discrete, pre-programmed steps.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] The earliest thermal cyclers were designed for use with the Klenow fragment of DNA polymerase I.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] Since this enzyme is destroyed during each heating step of the amplification process, new enzyme had to be added every cycle.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] This led to a cumbersome machine based on an automated pipettor, with open reaction tubes.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] Later, the PCR process was adapted to the use of thermostable DNA polymerase from *Thermus aquaticus*, which greatly simplified the design of the thermal cycler.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] While in some old machines the block is submerged in an oil bath to control temperature, in modern PCR machines a Peltier element is commonly used.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] Quality thermal cyclers often contain silver blocks to achieve fast temperature changes and uniform temperature throughout the block.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] Other cyclers have multiple blocks with high heat capacity, each of which is kept at a constant temperature, and the reaction tubes are moved between them by means of an automated process.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] Miniaturized thermal cyclers have been created in which the reaction mixture moves via channel through hot and cold zones on a microfluidic chip.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] Thermal cyclers designed for quantitative PCR have optical systems which enable fluorescence to be monitored during reaction cycling.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] Modern thermal cyclers are equipped with a heated lid that presses against the lids of the reaction tubes.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] This prevents condensation of water from the reaction mixtures on the insides of the lids.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] Traditionally, a layer of mineral oil was used for this purpose.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] Some thermal cyclers are equipped with a fully adjustable heated lid to allow for nonstandard or diverse types of PCR plasticware.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] Some thermal cyclers are equipped with multiple blocks allowing several different PCRs to be carried out simultaneously.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] Some models also have a *gradient* function to allow for different temperatures in different parts of the block.
[src:pcr-amplification/thermal-cycler] This is particularly useful when testing suitable annealing temperatures for PCR primers.
